<subSubSection lastPageId="16" lastPageNumber="47" pageId="14" pageNumber="45" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="14.[264,1323,284,1899]" lastBlockId="15.[264,1324,284,668]" lastPageId="15" lastPageNumber="46" pageId="14" pageNumber="45">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,453,1039,1065]" pageId="14" pageNumber="45">Discussion:</emphasis>
For bipaliid species where the copulatory apparatus is known (as in the 
<collectingCountry box="[264,371,1079,1105]" name="Bermuda" pageId="14" pageNumber="45">Bermuda</collectingCountry>
species), 
<bibRefCitation author="Ogren, R. E. &amp; Sluys" box="[492,760,1079,1105]" pageId="14" pageNumber="45" pagination="77 - 82" refId="ref11378" refString="Ogren, R. E. &amp; Sluys (1998) Selected characters of the copulatory organs in the land planarian family Bipaliidae and their taxonomic significance (Tricladida: Terricola). Hydrobiologia, 383, 77 - 82." type="journal article" year="1998">Ogren &amp; Sluys (1998)</bibRefCitation>
tentatively grouped bipaliids according to four characters of the copulatory apparatus. The 
<collectingCountry box="[782,889,1118,1144]" name="Bermuda" pageId="14" pageNumber="45">Bermuda</collectingCountry>
species has the following characters (definitions of abbreviations given in 
<bibRefCitation author="Ogren, R. E. &amp; Sluys" box="[706,953,1158,1184]" pageId="14" pageNumber="45" pagination="77 - 82" refId="ref11378" refString="Ogren, R. E. &amp; Sluys (1998) Selected characters of the copulatory organs in the land planarian family Bipaliidae and their taxonomic significance (Tricladida: Terricola). Hydrobiologia, 383, 77 - 82." type="journal article" year="1998">Ogren &amp; Sluys 1998</bibRefCitation>
): female organ is vertical (FCA 1); ovovitelline duct approaches the female canal from the posterior (OVD 0); penis papilla of the fixed conical 
<typeStatus box="[603,653,1238,1264]" pageId="14" pageNumber="45">type</typeStatus>
enclosing a large part of the ejaculatory duct (PPT 0); Male antrum wall is muscular and forms a prominent narrow penis sheath separating the male antrum from the common antrum (MAW 1). These are the characters of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stimpson" authorityYear="1857" box="[1215,1322,1317,1342]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Bipaliidae" genus="Bipalium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seriata" pageId="14" pageNumber="45" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1215,1322,1317,1342]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="45">Bipalium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group as defined by 
<bibRefCitation author="Ogren, R. E. &amp; Sluys" box="[519,795,1357,1383]" pageId="14" pageNumber="45" pagination="77 - 82" refId="ref11378" refString="Ogren, R. E. &amp; Sluys (1998) Selected characters of the copulatory organs in the land planarian family Bipaliidae and their taxonomic significance (Tricladida: Terricola). Hydrobiologia, 383, 77 - 82." type="journal article" year="1998">Ogren &amp; Sluys (1998)</bibRefCitation>
. The genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kawakatsu, Ogren &amp; E.M.Froehlich" authorityYear="1998" box="[947,1106,1357,1382]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Geoplanidae" genus="Novibipalium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tricladida" pageId="14" pageNumber="45" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[947,1106,1357,1382]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="45">Novibipalium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was proposed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Kawakatsu, M. &amp; Ogren, R. E. &amp; Froehlich, E. M." box="[264,544,1396,1422]" pageId="14" pageNumber="45" pagination="83 - 93" refId="ref10932" refString="Kawakatsu, M., Ogren, R. E. &amp; Froehlich, E. M. (1998) The taxonomic revision of several homonyms in the genus Bipalium, family Bipaliidae (Turbellaria, Seriata, Tricladida, Terricola). Bulletin of Fuji Women's University, No 36, Ser. II, 83 - 93." type="journal article" year="1998">
Kawakatsu 
<emphasis box="[401,452,1397,1422]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="45">et al</emphasis>
. (1998)
</bibRefCitation>
for those bipaliid species with a reduced penis papilla and an elongate penis sheath (pseudophallus). The 
<collectingCountry box="[739,846,1436,1462]" name="Bermuda" pageId="14" pageNumber="45">Bermuda</collectingCountry>
specimen has a penis papilla thus does not fit that definition. The genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ogren &amp; Sluys" authorityYear="2001" box="[665,813,1476,1501]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Geoplanidae" genus="Humbertium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tricladida" pageId="14" pageNumber="45" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[665,813,1476,1501]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="45">Humbertium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was erected by 
<bibRefCitation author="Ogren, R. E. &amp; Sluys" box="[1011,1278,1476,1502]" pageId="14" pageNumber="45" pagination="201 - 204" refId="ref11419" refString="Ogren, R. E. &amp; Sluys (2001) The genus Humbertium gen. nov., a new taxon of the land planarian family Bipaliidae (Tricladida, Terricola). Belgian Journal of Zoology, 131 (Supplement 1), 201 - 204." type="journal article" year="2001">Ogren &amp; Sluys (2001)</bibRefCitation>
for Groups B­1 and B­2 of 
<bibRefCitation author="Ogren, R. E. &amp; Sluys" box="[557,832,1516,1542]" pageId="14" pageNumber="45" pagination="77 - 82" refId="ref11378" refString="Ogren, R. E. &amp; Sluys (1998) Selected characters of the copulatory organs in the land planarian family Bipaliidae and their taxonomic significance (Tricladida: Terricola). Hydrobiologia, 383, 77 - 82." type="journal article" year="1998">Ogren &amp; Sluys (1998)</bibRefCitation>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ogren &amp; Sluys" authorityYear="2001" box="[845,993,1516,1541]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Geoplanidae" genus="Humbertium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tricladida" pageId="14" pageNumber="45" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[845,993,1516,1541]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="45">Humbertium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
includes species with ovovitelline ducts that turn dorsally anterior to the level of the gonopore. This is not the case in the 
<collectingCountry box="[338,445,1595,1621]" name="Bermuda" pageId="14" pageNumber="45">Bermuda</collectingCountry>
specimens. Bipaliid species incompletely described or described on external characters only are placed in the collective genus 
<taxonomicName authority="(Kawakatsu et al. 2002)" baseAuthorityName="Kawakatsu" baseAuthorityYear="2002" class="Rhabditophora" family="Geoplanidae" genus="Diversibipalium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tricladida" pageId="14" pageNumber="45" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[912,1102,1635,1660]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="45">Diversibipalium</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Kawakatsu, M. &amp; Ogren, R. E. &amp; Froehlich, E. M. &amp; Sasaki, G-Y." pageId="14" pageNumber="45" pagination="162 - 177" refId="ref10993" refString="Kawakatsu, M., Ogren, R. E., Froehlich, E. M. &amp; Sasaki, G-Y. (2002) Additions and corrections of the previous terrestrial planarian indices of the World (Turbellaria, Seriata, Tricladida, Terricola) - 10. Bulletin of Fuji Women's University, No 40, Ser. II, 162 - 177." type="journal article" year="2002">
Kawakatsu 
<emphasis box="[1261,1316,1635,1660]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="45">et al</emphasis>
. 2002
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. External characters could be used to identify the 
<collectingCountry box="[954,1061,1674,1700]" name="Bermuda" pageId="14" pageNumber="45">Bermuda</collectingCountry>
specimens with such species. 
<bibRefCitation author="Graff, L. von" box="[363,513,1714,1740]" pageId="14" pageNumber="45" refId="ref10820" refString="Graff, L. von (1899) Monographie der Turbellarien II. Tricladida, Terricola. Leipzig, W. Engelmann." type="book" year="1899">Graff (1899)</bibRefCitation>
, in his identification key, lists 14 bipaliid species with three dark dorsal stripes. The 
<collectingCountry box="[462,569,1754,1780]" name="Bermuda" pageId="14" pageNumber="45">Bermuda</collectingCountry>
specimens match none of these. 
<bibRefCitation author="Ogren, R. E." box="[984,1148,1754,1780]" pageId="14" pageNumber="45" pagination="21 - 30" refId="ref11166" refString="Ogren, R. E. (1987) Description of a new three-lined land planarian of the genus Bipalium (Turbellaria: Tricladida) from Pennsylvania, U. S. A. Transactions of the American Microscopical Society, 106, 21 - 30." type="journal article" year="1987">Ogren (1987)</bibRefCitation>
lists a further seven species with three dark dorsal stripes. The only species with three stripes beginning at a darkly pigmented neck (as in the 
<collectingCountry box="[720,827,1833,1859]" name="Bermuda" pageId="14" pageNumber="45">Bermuda</collectingCountry>
specimens) is 
<taxonomicName authority="(Saxena 1957)" baseAuthorityName="Saxena" baseAuthorityYear="1957" box="[1008,1319,1833,1859]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Geoplanidae" genus="Diversibipalium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tricladida" pageId="14" pageNumber="45" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="keshavi">
<emphasis box="[1008,1134,1834,1859]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="45">D. keshavi</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Saxena, P. N." box="[1151,1310,1833,1859]" pageId="14" pageNumber="45" pagination="301 - 302" refId="ref11514" refString="Saxena, P. N. (1957) A new species of Bipalium from Nepal. Abstracts of the Indian Scientific Congress Association Proceedings, 44, 301 - 302." type="journal article" year="1957">Saxena 1957</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. The original description by 
<bibRefCitation author="Saxena, P. N." box="[603,776,1873,1899]" pageId="14" pageNumber="45" pagination="301 - 302" refId="ref11514" refString="Saxena, P. N. (1957) A new species of Bipalium from Nepal. Abstracts of the Indian Scientific Congress Association Proceedings, 44, 301 - 302." type="journal article" year="1957">Saxena (1957)</bibRefCitation>
is extremely brief, 16 lines in total, with no illustrations and is of external characters only. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Saxena" baseAuthorityYear="1957" box="[841,1131,284,309]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Geoplanidae" genus="Diversibipalium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tricladida" pageId="15" pageNumber="46" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="keshavi">
<emphasis box="[841,1131,284,309]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="46">Diversibipalium keshavi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is described as light brown to grey in colour, 
<quantity box="[627,770,324,350]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="0.8" pageId="15" pageNumber="46" unit="mm" value="140.0" valueMax="200.0" valueMin="80.0">80–200 mm</quantity>
long and 
<quantity box="[893,992,324,350]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="15" pageNumber="46" unit="mm" value="4.0" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="3.0">3–5 mm</quantity>
wide. A median dorsal and two lateral dark stripes (no information as to colour or relative width) extend from the neck which is darkly pigmented (again, no information as to colour). Thus, though the 
<collectingCountry box="[264,371,443,469]" name="Bermuda" pageId="15" pageNumber="46">Bermuda</collectingCountry>
specimens 
<emphasis box="[508,573,443,468]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="46">could</emphasis>
belong to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Saxena" baseAuthorityYear="1957" box="[699,823,443,468]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Geoplanidae" genus="Diversibipalium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tricladida" pageId="15" pageNumber="46" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="keshavi">
<emphasis box="[699,823,443,468]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="46">D. keshavi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the description of the latter is inadequate. Further, the 
<collectingCountry box="[406,514,482,508]" name="Bermuda" pageId="15" pageNumber="46">Bermuda</collectingCountry>
specimens are fully mature yet much shorter than the reported length of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Saxena" baseAuthorityYear="1957" box="[296,419,522,547]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Geoplanidae" genus="Diversibipalium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tricladida" pageId="15" pageNumber="46" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="keshavi">
<emphasis box="[296,419,522,547]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="46">D. keshavi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
so it seems unlikely that they are of that species. Thus we place the 
<collectingCountry box="[1213,1320,522,548]" name="Bermuda" pageId="15" pageNumber="46">Bermuda</collectingCountry>
specimen in the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stimpson" authorityYear="1857" box="[529,636,562,587]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Bipaliidae" genus="Bipalium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seriata" pageId="15" pageNumber="46" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[529,636,562,587]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="46">Bipalium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as currently defined, hence 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jones &amp; Sterrer" authorityYear="2005" box="[964,1156,562,587]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Bipaliidae" genus="Bipalium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seriata" pageId="15" pageNumber="46" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="vagum">
<emphasis box="[964,1156,562,587]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="46">Bipalium vagum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Certainly the copulatory apparatus is similar in its general characteristics to that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moseley" authorityYear="1878" box="[1073,1203,602,627]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Bipaliidae" genus="Bipalium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seriata" pageId="15" pageNumber="46" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="kewense">
<emphasis box="[1073,1203,602,627]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="46">B. kewense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see 
<bibRefCitation author="Winsor, L." pageId="15" pageNumber="46" pagination="61 - 100" refId="ref11728" refString="Winsor, L. (1983) A revision of the land planarian Bipalium kewense Mosely, 1878 (Turbellaria; Tricladida; Terricola). Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society, 79, 61 - 100." type="journal article" year="1983">Winsor 1983</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
